06146nam a22008415i 9781442685857DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172013onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426858577 a10.3138/97814426858572doi  a(DE-B1597)482995  a(OCoLC)1004871792  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aNX650.E46bS77 2013 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a306.4090321 aMcClary, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStructures of Feeling in Seventeenth-Century Cultural Expression /cSusan McClary. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aUCLA Clark Memorial Library Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction: On Bodies, Affects, and Cultural Identities in the Seventeenth Century -- tPart I: The Science of Affect -- t1. Disciplining Feeling: The Seventeenth-Century Idea of a Mathematical Theory of the Emotions -- t2. Clockwork or Musical Instrument? Some English Theories of Mind-Body Interaction before and after Descartes -- t3. The Sound World of Father Mersenne -- tPart II: Colonial Extensions -- t4. ‘Voluntary Subjection’: France’s Theory of Colonization/ Culture in the Seventeenth Century -- t5. Fear of Singing (Episodes from Early Latin America) -- t6. The Illicit Voice of Prophecy -- tPart III: The Politics of Opera -- t7. Daphne’s Dilemma: Desire as Metamorphosis in Early Modern Opera -- t8. A Viceroy behind the Scenes: Opera, Production, Politics, and Financing in 1680s Naples -- tPart IV: Baroque Bodies -- t9. Crashaw and the Metaphysical Shudder; Or, How to Do Things with Tears -- t10. ‘Law’s Bloody Inflictions’: Judicial Wounding and Resistance in Seventeenth-Century England -- t11. Excursions to See ‘Monsters’: Odd Bodies and Itineraries of Knowledge in the Seventeenth Century -- tPart V: Toward a History of Time and Subjectivity -- t12. Temporality and Ideology: Qualities of Motion in Seventeenth-Century French Music -- t13. Temporal Interventions: Music, Modernity, and the Presentation of the Self -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween the waning of the Renaissance and the beginning of the Enlightenment, many fundamental aspects of human behaviour - from expressions of gender to the experience of time - underwent radical changes. While some of these transformations were recorded in words, others have survived in non-verbal cultural media, notably the visual arts, poetry, theatre, music, and dance. Structures of Feeling in Seventeenth-Century Cultural Expression explores how artists made use of these various cultural forms to grapple with human values in the increasingly heterodox world of the 1600s.Essays from prominent historians, musicologists, and art critics examine methods of non-verbal cultural expression through the broad themes of time, motion, the body, and global relations. Together, they show that seventeenth-century cultural expression was more than just an embryonic stage within Western artistic development. Instead, the contributors argue that this period marks some of the most profound changes in European subjectivities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArts, Moderny17th centuryvCongresses. 0aEmotionsxHistoryy17th centuryvCongresses. 0aExpressionxHistoryy17th centuryvCongresses. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh1 aBloechl, Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristensen, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCovington, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarber,